Maria Bamford. She's my favorite comedian. Number two is Kyle Kinane.

00:06:30.679 --> 00:06:35.559
Well, David, thanks so much for the intro and sharing a little bit about your background

00:06:35.559 --> 00:06:40.920
there. I know when we were chatting, you shared some more info on how you had previously worked

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:46.119
in IT as well. And so I was just curious to kick off the conversation with that because

00:06:46.119 --> 00:06:52.040
it's something that comes up quite a bit in this space, but having moved from IT to data science,

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:56.760
I know you have probably pretty unique perspectives on both sides. What would

00:06:56.760 --> 00:07:02.200
you recommend to some of us who might be struggling to communicate across those lines?

00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:06.839
That's a good question. And, you know, I think a challenge that I hear in the Hangouts and then

00:07:06.839 --> 00:07:14.600
also just kind of conversations I've had with other people, you know, to me, a lot of times you

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:19.000
have these challenges and it really just kind of boils down to building a good relationship,

00:07:19.559 --> 00:07:24.359
you know, so that can pan out in a lot of different ways. And it's really dependent

00:07:24.359 --> 00:07:29.320
on your organization and I think how it's set up and just, you know, kind of the general size of it.

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:39.000
The way that we did it was, you know, we kind of built data science, you know, not quite from

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:44.839
scratch, but we had one organization at Enpo that did some sort of kind of data science-y work.

00:07:44.839 --> 00:07:50.279
And then our senior leadership team kind of identified it as a strategic priority for

00:07:50.279 --> 00:07:55.000
the company to actually build out that capability. So then there was a lot of emphasis and a lot of

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:02.440
focus on it. And that was right after I had moved into the data science organization. So we knew

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:07.559
that, you know, data science and IT needed to work together because, I mean, every single project that

00:08:07.559 --> 00:08:16.839
we work on has an IT component to it. So some of what we did is we started having leadership

00:08:16.839 --> 00:08:20.760
meetings between data science leadership and IT leadership on some sort of regular cadence,

00:08:20.760 --> 00:08:26.200
just to kind of talk about what the roadmaps look like, what projects are on the horizon,

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:31.480
what challenges there might be, and just kind of putting everything out in the open as much as you

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:37.880
can just to have those conversations. You know, on a more personal level, I think it's really

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:44.280
important for the two groups to kind of learn more about what each group does, you know. So

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:49.960
sit down with a network engineer and understand why, you know, they might be a little cautious

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:56.440
about opening up all of, you know, opening up their infrastructure to all of the packages on a

00:08:56.440 --> 00:09:02.200
repo or, you know, having a network engineer sit down with a data scientist and understand why

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:08.520
that's a challenge for them. It really, to me, just kind of comes down to having conversations

00:09:08.520 --> 00:09:14.679
and being open and honest and transparent and figuring out a way to move forward together.

00:09:14.679 --> 00:09:20.440
That's great. How did you actually first start those conversations? I think you said it was at

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:24.760
the senior leadership level, but was there something that kind of drove those initial

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:33.719
conversations? Well, so data science kind of became an emphasis for ENPO because the way

00:09:33.719 --> 00:09:40.119
that we were doing business was changing. So we go out and evaluate stations every two years. That's

00:09:40.119 --> 00:09:45.799
kind of been the regular cadence for about 30 years. But a lot can happen in between those

00:09:45.799 --> 00:09:51.000
two-year assessments, right? So we understood that we needed to get into more of a kind of a

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:55.640
continuous monitoring sort of fashion. And the only way that we can do that, because we don't

00:09:55.640 --> 00:10:00.119
want to go out and evaluate more often, it's a really costly thing to set up an evaluation team

00:10:00.119 --> 00:10:05.719
and send it to a station. So instead, it meant that we needed to figure out a way to use the data

00:10:05.719 --> 00:10:10.599
that we have to do some modeling, some analysis, and try to kind of understand what their

00:10:10.599 --> 00:10:15.640
quote-unquote performance looks like in between those evaluations. So that was kind of

00:10:15.640 --> 00:10:21.640
where it landed at a strategic level. And then it kind of became our job to actually

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:28.840
implement that. And having recently, it was real lucky having moved

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:33.159
right from IT to data science and being able to kind of bring that perspective to both sides,

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:37.960
you know, I think put us in a really good situation. But I know that's kind of a rare

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:45.559
situation to be in, too. So, you know, I think, yeah, just kind of like sitting down,

00:10:45.559 --> 00:10:49.000
you know, putting your chairs in a circle and saying, what's going on? What can we work on?

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:53.640
How do we figure this all out together? It's just kind of the right way to start.

00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:59.159
Yeah, thank you. Russ, I see you asked a question in the chat. Do you want to jump in here?

00:10:59.159 --> 00:11:05.960
Yeah, thank you. I have a master's in counseling. I love humanistic psychology. I could talk to you

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:10.359
about that all day. Does that help you in data science? If so, can you say something about that?

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:16.760
I thought about that, you know, kind of in preparation for that talk. And the more that

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:22.840
I thought about it, the more kind of threads that I could see. Just because, you know, a lot of data

00:11:22.840 --> 00:11:28.119
science and a lot of working in an organization in general is kind of working on relationships

00:11:28.119 --> 00:11:35.000
and communication. And actually, you know, actively listening, you know, that was something

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:41.559
I remember taking a class on that when I was in college. And I feel like I still, you know,

00:11:41.559 --> 00:11:45.000
try to use those skills to this day where, you know, you're actually sitting there in front of

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:49.159
a person and you're hearing what they say and you're thinking about what they say instead of

00:11:49.719 --> 00:11:53.320
figuring out what you're just going to say next. So, you know, kind of having a real active

00:11:53.320 --> 00:12:00.760
listening sort of conversation. And then understanding that, you know, people are people

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:09.239
and we can be inconsistent and hard to understand. And, you know, really all it takes is maybe a

00:12:09.239 --> 00:12:16.280
little bit of openness and kindness to give space to the sorts of conversations that need to happen.

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:20.520
You know, the sorts of kind of crucial conversations that we have. We call it,

00:12:20.520 --> 00:12:25.400
that's kind of a term that we use at INPO for these sort of intense conversations

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:31.960
that need some sort of resolution. And, you know, in my opinion, just kind of being open to that

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:36.679
and understanding that, you know, there's going to be some emotional reactions and that's A-OK

00:12:36.679 --> 00:12:41.799
because we're all human beings. But it's important to not, you know, just kind of react to them

00:12:42.359 --> 00:12:48.440
and just fan the flames. You need to figure out what the sources of the issue and address that.

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:52.280
Love that. Thank you. Alan, I see you have a question here. You want to jump in?

