nuclear power is really, really specific, like a super specific domain. If that's the case,

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:09.239
I wonder how that domain expertise comes to play in the stuff you do day to day,

00:13:09.239 --> 00:13:14.919
or if maybe that's the wrong assumption and really the metrics are around efficiency and people

00:13:14.919 --> 00:13:18.200
metrics and like things that aren't really familiar. Like, I wonder how specific what

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:23.719
you're doing is to that industry and, you know, how you operate in that kind of environment.

00:13:25.080 --> 00:13:30.679
That's an excellent question. So the industry metrics we get, we get hundreds of data points

00:13:30.679 --> 00:13:38.359
from every station every month. And we use that to, we end up, you know, because every station

00:13:38.359 --> 00:13:41.400
can be a little different. You've got to, you know, go through some sort of, you know, kind

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:47.640
of like normalization scheme. So we have these indicators that are a way that we normalize the

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:53.719
data. And then that's what we can actually do some modeling on. And I have learned just how

00:13:53.719 --> 00:13:58.359
little I know about nuclear power by moving to the industry side of things and needing to

00:13:58.359 --> 00:14:04.840
understand exactly what, you know, every label, every acronym means. And it'll take a really long

00:14:04.840 --> 00:14:09.640
time to get to that point. And luckily I don't need all of that to do my day to day job. But,

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:14.280
you know, whenever I'm working on a really important model, I've got to make sure that

00:14:14.280 --> 00:14:19.640
I'm not making some really bad assumptions about it. So that, you know, means that I got to sit

00:14:19.640 --> 00:14:24.039
down and talk with my manager, director, or some other subject matter experts in some of the

00:14:24.039 --> 00:14:30.359
functional areas here at INPO, just to kind of, you know, make sure that whatever I don't know

00:14:30.359 --> 00:14:34.280
isn't going to actually bite me sometime. So yeah, that's a great comment.

