Thanks.

00:14:36.280 --> 00:14:40.840
I know you mentioned data science is relatively new for INPO.

00:14:42.280 --> 00:14:47.159
How have you been successful in introducing data science and data science tools?

00:14:50.840 --> 00:14:59.400
Great question. So, you know, introducing like a new tool to the enterprise is a really challenging

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:03.559
thing. You can't just, you know, say here are some model results and expect everyone to understand

00:15:03.559 --> 00:15:10.359
what that means. So one of the changes that we've made, and it's actually kind of part of

00:15:10.359 --> 00:15:15.799
our governance that we've written, is that anytime there is, you know, a new tool of some sort

00:15:16.599 --> 00:15:25.479
delivered, we have to figure out a way to explain it or interpret it with some other, you know,

00:15:25.479 --> 00:15:30.359
maybe some other tool or maybe, you know, kind of a help function of some sort. So, you know,

00:15:30.359 --> 00:15:36.919
one of the things that we've learned is that, you know, delivering these model results that

00:15:36.919 --> 00:15:43.159
require some subtlety and understanding is hard to do for people that don't use it on a real

00:15:43.159 --> 00:15:49.719
frequent basis. So, you know, we've added a lot more kind of like help functions into the tools

00:15:49.719 --> 00:15:54.599
that we build, the ways that we expose these model results. And then we've also, you know,

00:15:54.599 --> 00:16:01.960
kind of built some other tools to, I got to talk generally, to help you understand why the model

00:16:01.960 --> 00:16:08.200
is saying what it's saying. And we've had a lot of success in, you know, kind of thinking about

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:14.200
things from, you know, the end user perspective and not at the data science perspective to help

00:16:14.200 --> 00:16:20.760
us figure out exactly what we can do better to make sure that they use the tool correctly and

00:16:20.760 --> 00:16:26.280
they get the insight that they want out of it. I guess kind of maybe this follows along with

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:29.880
this a little bit, and no worries if there's certain things you can't share with us. But

00:16:29.880 --> 00:16:35.640
there was an anonymous question that was, what kind of data science use cases can you share with

00:16:35.640 --> 00:16:42.520
us in the nuclear industry and in your company? Yeah. So, you know, what I kind of alluded to

00:16:42.520 --> 00:16:47.239
earlier is, you know, what kind of the impetus for data science at EMBA was trying to understand

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:54.440
performance in between the assessments every two years, biannual, biannual, I never remember the

00:16:54.440 --> 00:17:03.640
word. So, you know, we get data from the industry every month and we have a model that helps us

00:17:03.640 --> 00:17:08.520
gauge that sort of performance in between the assessments, right? So, the assessments are kind

00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:13.239
of our gold standard in the way that we know if the model is right or wrong, but it gives us

00:17:14.119 --> 00:17:22.280
an estimate in between for their performance. And then, you know, from there, there are other

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:28.599
things where you can, you know, maybe kind of come up with some risk models to see if something,

00:17:28.599 --> 00:17:35.000
you know, has a high probability of happening. And, you know, we don't, obviously don't want

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:41.400
it to happen. So, we want to figure out that risk and try to get ahead of it. Let's see,

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:46.280
what else we got? I'm going to stop there, just, you know, just to make sure I keep it

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:54.439
general enough. Sorry. That's okay. So, when you share those models, who are you sharing them with

00:17:54.439 --> 00:18:01.560
or how do you share the model with broader stakeholder groups? So, you know, data science

00:18:01.560 --> 00:18:07.959
at ENPO, our department is actually called data science and it's composed of kind of three groups.

00:18:07.959 --> 00:18:14.760
So, one is data visualization. One is kind of data analytics and that's where I live. And then

00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:21.959
one is data quality or data management. I think we call it data quality. So, you know, whenever I

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:28.280
build a model, you know, I'm just kind of having the results end up in a database somewhere.

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:34.280
And then we rely on our incredibly capable data visualization group to actually kind of build

00:18:34.280 --> 00:18:39.880
those visualizations to deliver it to an end user. So, you know, no one ever really gets those raw

00:18:39.880 --> 00:18:45.239
results out of the database. They get something within a broader context to help them, to help

00:18:45.239 --> 00:18:52.040
make sure that they are interpreting it correctly. Thank you. Sure. Let me jump over to one other

00:18:52.839 --> 00:18:59.079
anonymous question first here. And one was, pharma has a huge emphasis on a very muddled concept of

00:18:59.079 --> 00:19:04.839
validation. Is there something like this perception of regulatory overhead that affects your work?

00:19:06.040 --> 00:19:12.040
That exists within the nuclear industry, but it doesn't affect ENPO. So, there is – I remember

00:19:12.040 --> 00:19:17.880
when I worked at IT, there's a group called – it's called NITSL, N-I-T-S-L, the Nuclear

00:19:17.880 --> 00:19:23.160
Information Technology and Strategic Leadership Group, which is kind of a more nuclear IT group,

00:19:23.719 --> 00:19:31.239
working group. And they have a focus on quality assurance because there are very strict regulations

00:19:31.239 --> 00:19:39.079
that go into how you validate that a system, that like a software system is going to do what you say

00:19:39.079 --> 00:19:46.199
it's going to do as long as, you know, it's going to do what you say it's going to do and it's going

00:19:46.199 --> 00:19:50.920
to work correctly and there's no way that it can kind of, you know, get it wrong. But that mostly

00:19:50.920 --> 00:19:56.199
affects the safety systems at a nuclear station. As far as I understand, this is obviously, you know,

00:19:56.199 --> 00:20:03.239
not my wheelhouse. But because we at ENPO don't work directly with, you know, kind of supporting

